=begin slide 
=title Linux: How to get it

On Windows or Mac:

=item Use B<Putty> to connect to a cloud server (as cheap as $2.50 per month)

=item Install the Windows 10 Ubuntu subsystem

=item Use a live, bootable USB [recommended for intro]

=item Use a live, bootable CD/DVD [only as a last resort]
=end slide 

=begin slide 
=title Linux: How to get it

=item Install Linux as a VM guest on Windows 10 Pro Hyper-V

=item Install VirtualBox to run a Linux Virtual Machine

=item Use I<Cygwin> on Windows

Best:

=item Use a dual-boot, native installation

=item Use Hyper-V on Windows 10 Pro

=item Use a dedicated GNU/Linux PC or laptop
=end slide 

=begin slide 
=title Linux comes in many "flavors"

A Linux system comes packaged in many B<distributions> such as
Debian, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, and others.

See L<https://distrowatch.com> for lots of information about
popularity, download statistics, and other stats on hundreds of
B<distros>.

My Linux friends think I<Linux Mint> is one of the best I<distros> for beginners. I
prefer I<Debian> and have used it for over ten years
=end slide 

